'''Camolin''', according to a 2004 report in the German magazine [[Der Spiegel]], is a secret [[counter-terrorism]] unit based in [[Paris]], [[France]].  The article states that the USA, UK, Australia, Germany, and France - amongst others - created this unit after the [[September 11 attacks|11 September 2001 attacks]] on the US.  Started as [[Alliance Base]] in 2002, the unit is now codenamed Camolin.

Their greatest success to date seems to have been the arrest in France on 3 June 2003, of the German [[Muslim]] convert [[Christian Ganczarski]] who was considered at the time to be the head of [[Al Qaeda]] in Europe.

