{{Infobox ancient site | name = <!-- required -->Tell Muḥammad | native_name = Diniktum | alternate_name = | image = | alt = | caption = | map_type = Iraq | map_alt = | map_caption = | map_size = | relief = yes | coordinates = {{coord|33|17|37.0752|N|44|28|58.4112|E|display=inline,title}} | location = [[Baghdad]], [[Baghdad Governorate]], [[Iraq]] | region = [[Mesopotamia]] | type = [[Tell (archaeology)|tell]] | part_of = | length = | width = | area = | height = | builder = | material = | built = | abandoned = | epochs = <!-- actually displays as "Periods" --> | cultures = | dependency_of = | occupants = | event = | excavations = | archaeologists = | condition = | ownership = | management = | public_access = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | notes = }}
'''Diniktum''', inscribed ''Di-ni-ik-tum''<sup>KI</sup>, was a middle bronze-age town located somewhere in the lower Diyala region of [[Mesopotamia]], on the [[Tigris]] river downstream from [[Opis|Upi]] and close to the northern border of [[Elam]]. It is possibly at or in the vicinity of Tell Muḥammad, which lies in south-eastern part of modern [[Baghdad]]. <ref>Paolo Gentili, Where is Diniktum? : Remarks on the Situation and a Supposition, Rivista degli studi orientali, Nuova Serie, Vol. 79, Fasc. 1/4, pp. 231-238, 2006</ref> It is mentioned in the Harmal geographical list.<ref>Tablet IM 51143.</ref>
==History==
It enjoyed independence briefly during the 18th century under the reigns of the Amorite chieftains (''ra-bí-an'' MAR.DÚ) Itur-šarrum, attested on a single seal from [[Eshnunna|Ešnunna]], and Sîn-gāmil, son of Sîn-šēmi and a contemporary of [[Zimrilim|Zimri-Lim]] (ca. 1710–1698 BC [[Short chronology timeline|short]]) of [[Mari, Syria|Mari]] and [[Hammurabi|Ḫammu-rapī]] (ca. 1728–1686 BC short) of [[Babylon]].<ref>{{ cite book | title = Old Babylonian period (2003-1595 BC): Early Periods, Volume 4 (RIM The Royal Inscriptions of Mesopotamia) | author = Douglas Frayne | publisher = University of Toronto Press | year = 1990 | pages = 682–685 }}</ref> In an old Babylonian letter from [[Yarim-Lim I]], the king of [[Yamhad|Iamḫad]] whose capital was Halab, ancient [[Aleppo]], to the Yašub-Yahad, the king of [[Der (Sumer)|Dēr]], he says:
{{ quote|.. Certainly. Sîn-gāmil, king of Diniktum. very much like you would repeatedly respond to me by means of lies and provocations. Having docked 500 boats in Diniktum's quay. I "sank" (supported?) his land as well as him for 12 year!"<ref>{{ cite book | title = Editions Recherche sur Ies Civilisations | chapter = Yarim-Lim's War Declaration | author = J. Sasson | location = Paris | year = 1985 | page = 244 }}</ref>|Iarīm-Līm|Tablet A. 1314, Letter to Yašub-Yahad }}
Ikūn-pî-Sîn (“The word of Sin is truthful”), the ruler of Nērebtum and possibly [[Tutub]], cities in the sphere of Ešnunna, has a year name: “Year when Ikū(n)-pî-Sîn captured Diniktum." It was absorbed into the kingdom of Ešnunna and consequently embroiled in its conflicts with Elam during the reigns of Ibāl-pî-El II (ca. 1715–1701 BC short) and Ṣillī-Sîn (ca. 1700–1698 BC short).<ref>{{ cite book | title = The Routledge Handbook of The People and Places of Ancient Western Asia | author = Trevor Bryce | publisher = Routledge | year = 2009 | page = 196 }}</ref> The town was still settled in the later bronze-age, as a year name gives ““the year [in which] [[Kadashman-harbe I|Kadašman-Ḫarbe]], the king, dug the canal of Diniktum.”<ref>Tablet Ni. 3199.</ref> Kadašman-Ḫarbe was a [[Kassites|Kassite]] king of Babylon of the late 15th century.
