'''Hørsholm Arboretum''' ({{lang-da|Arboretet i Hørsholm}}) is an [[arboretum]] located in [[Hørsholm]], 20&nbsp;km north of [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. It operates as part of the [[University of Copenhagen]]'s Department of Geosciences and Natural Resource Management.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Arboretum in Hørsholm|url=http://ign.ku.dk/arboretum-hoersholm/|website=Department of Geosciences and Natural Resource Management|publisher=University of Copenhagen Faculty of Science|accessdate=19 January 2016}}</ref>

==Arboretum==
Hørsholm Arboretum was established by the [[Royal Veterinary and Agricultural University]] in 1936 as an off-site expansion of the [[Forstbotanisk Have|Forestry Botanical Garden]] in [[Charlottenlund]]. With its approximately 2&nbsp;000 species of trees and shrubs, Hørsholm Arboretum is the largest arboretum in Denmark.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ign.ku.dk/arboretum-hoersholm/about-aboretum/|title=About the Arboretum in Hørsholm|website=Department of Geosciences and Natural Resource Management|publisher=University of Copenhagen Faculty of Science|accessdate=19 January 2016}}</ref>

==Buildings==
The Forest & Landscape research center was built in 1994&ndash;95 to design by royal building inspector Gehrdt Bornebusch. It has been designed to maximize the views of the arboretum and Ubberød Pond. The use of wood, both elm and pine, plays a prominent role in the architecture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arkark.dk/building.aspx?buildingid=2782|title=Hørsholm Forskningscenter for Skov og Landskab|language=Danish|website=arkark.dk|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> The building was left empty when the activities moved to Copenhagen in 2008 and the national property company Freja Ejendomme took over the buildings in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hoersholm.lokalavisen.dk/der-skal-stadig-forskes-i-tom-bygning-/20140417/artikler/704179930/1039|title=Der skal stadig forskes i tom bygning|language=Danish|website=ugebladet.dkUniversitet|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref>

==Public access==
Hørsholm Arboretum is open to the public daily from 6.39 until sunset. It is particularly popular with visitors in May when the extensive collection of wild rhododendron species blossom. The arboretum arranges tours and other events with support from  G.B. Hartmanns Forskningsfond.

