{{Infobox military installation | name = Ramla Right Battery | native_name = Batterija tal-Lemin tar-Ramla | location = [[Nadur]], [[Gozo]], [[Malta]] | image = Ramla Right Battery, Ramla Bay 001.jpg | image_size = 300px | caption = Ruins of Ramla Right Battery | type = [[Artillery battery]] | coordinates = {{coord|36|3|45.6|N|14|17|12.8|E|type:landmark|display=inline}} | ownership = [[Government of Malta]] | controlledby = Gaia Foundation | open_to_public = | built = 1715–1716 | used = | builder = [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of Saint John]] | materials = [[Limestone]] | height = | condition = Ruins | battles = [[Mediterranean campaign of 1798#Malta|French invasion of Malta (1798)]] | events = }}
'''Ramla Right Battery''' ({{lang-mt|Batterija tal-Lemin tar-Ramla}}), also known as '''Gironda Battery''' ({{lang-mt|Batterija ta' Gironda}})<ref>{{mt icon}} {{cite web|last1=Mifsud|first1=Raymond|title=It-Trunciera fir-Ramla|url=http://www.xaghra.com/article/postijiet-storici/it-trunciera-fir-ramla/|website=Xaghra.com|accessdate=2 August 2015}}</ref> or '''Nadur Battery''' ({{lang-mt|Batterija tan-Nadur}}),<ref>{{cite web|title=Scheduling of Property - Section 46 of the Development Planning Act, 1992|url=https://www.mepa.org.mt/file.aspx?f=599|website=MEPA|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ZbIOJ8Yz|archivedate=27 June 2015|date=6 January 1995}}</ref> was an [[artillery battery]] in [[Ramla Bay]], limits of [[Nadur]] on the island of [[Gozo]], [[Malta]]. It was built by the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of Saint John]] in 1715–1716 as one of a series of coastal fortifications around the Maltese Islands. The battery now lies in ruins.
==History== Ramla Right Battery was built in 1715–1716 as part of the first building programme of coastal batteries in Malta. It was one of several fortifications in Ramla Bay, which also included [[Ramla Left Battery]] on the opposite side of the bay and [[Ramla Redoubt]] in the centre. These were all linked together by an [[Entrenchment (fortification)|entrenchment]] wall. Ramla Bay was further defended by [[Marsalforn Tower]] on the plateau above the bay, and an underwater barrier to prevent enemy ships from landing within the bay.
The battery had a semi-circular parapet with six embrasures, with a blockhouse at the rear. A [[Fougasse (weapon)|fougasse]] was also dug on the shore close to the battery, and it still exists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Il-Bajja tar-Ramla|url=http://www.xaghra.com/article/postijiet-storici/il-bajja-tar-ramla/|website=Xaghra.com|accessdate=27 June 2015|language=Maltese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Saliba|first1=Mario|title=Ir-Ramla: ġawhra naturali u wirt nazzjonali.|url=https://www.academia.edu/3591456/Ir-Ramla_l-Hamra|website=academia.edu|accessdate=27 June 2015|language=Maltese}}</ref>
The battery saw use during the [[Mediterranean campaign of 1798#Malta|French invasion of Malta]] in 1798, when it fired on the approaching French fleet.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hardman|first1=William|title=A history of Malta during the period of the French and British occupations, 1798-1815|date=1909|publisher=Longmans, Green & Co|location=[[London]]|page=47|url=https://archive.org/stream/historyofmaltadu00hard#page/46/mode/2up}}</ref>
==Present day== Today, only some remains of the battery's blockhouse survive. These remains, along with the rest of Ramla Bay, are managed by the Gaia Foundation.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ragonesi|first1=Rudolf|title=Gaia Foundation and Ramla l-Ħamra|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20130616/environment/Gaia-Foundation-and-Ramla-l-amra.474029|accessdate=27 June 2015|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=16 June 2013}}</ref>
