{{Infobox song | name = We Are the Heroes | cover = Litesound_-_We_Are_the_Heroes.jpg | alt = | border = yes | type = single | artist = [[Litesound]] | album = | released = 18 March 2012 | format = [[Music streaming]] | recorded = 2012 | studio = | venue = | genre = [[Synthpop|Electropop]] | length = {{duration|m=3|s=00}} | label = West Records | writer = Dmitriy Karyakin, Vladimir Karyakin | producer = [[Dimitris Kontopoulos]] | prev_title = | prev_year = | next_title = | next_year = | misc = {{External music video|{{YouTube|LbUSs1BCiKY|"We Are the Heroes"}}}} {{Infobox song contest entry|embed=yes | song = {{Flag icon|Belarus}} "We Are The Heroes" | year = 2012 | country = Belarus | artist = Dmitriy and Vladimir Karyakin | as = [[Litesound]] | language = English | composer = Dmitriy Karyakin, Vladimir Karyakin | lyricist = Dmitriy Karyakin, Vladimir Karyakin | place_semi = 16th | points_semi = 35 | prev = I Love Belarus | prev_link = I Love Belarus | next = Solayoh | next_link = Solayoh }} }} "'''We Are the Heroes'''" is a song by Belarusian-Italian band [[Litesound]]. It represented [[Belarus in the Eurovision Song Contest 2012|Belarus]] in the second semi-final of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2012]].<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.eurovision.tv/page/baku-2012/about/shows/participants | publisher = Eurovision.tv | title = Eurovision Song Contest 2012 Semi-Finals | accessdate = 20 May 2012}}</ref>
The song was performed for the first time by Litesound on 21 December 2011, during the semi-final of the [[Belarus in the Eurovision Song Contest 2012|Eurofest 2012]], the national selection for the Belarusian entry to the Eurovision Song Contest 2012.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/17982 |publisher = ESCToday.com | accessdate = 29 February 2012 | title = Belarus: EuroFest final to be held on January 28th | date = 18 December 2011 | author = Victor Hondal}}</ref> During the final of the show, Litesound came in second place behind [[Alyona Lanskaya]],<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.eurovision.tv/page/news?id=46293&_t=alyona_lanskaya_to_represent_belarus |publisher = Eurovision.tv | accessdate = 29 February 2012 | title = Alyona Lanskaya to represent Belarus | date = 14 February 2012}}</ref> but they were later chosen to replace Lanskaya following an investigation about a fraud in the televote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurovisionary.com/eurovision-news/alena-lanskaya-will-not-be-going-baku-litesound-represent-belarus-instead |title=Alena Lanskaya will not be going to Baku - Litesound to represent Belarus instead &#124; Eurovision Song Contest 2012 in Baku |publisher=EuroVisionary |date= |accessdate=25 February 2012}}</ref>
The song was re-recorded in a new version, produced by [[Dimitris Kontopoulos]].<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/18542 | publisher = ESCToday.com | accessdate = 7 May 2012 | title = Belarus: Eurovision version for We are the heroes out | author = Victor Hondal | date = 18 March 2012}}</ref> The music video for the song was directed by Litesound's members Dmitri and Vladimir Karjakin.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.radiobelarus.tvr.by/eng/news.asp?type=cont&id=25638&date=13.4.2012 | publisher = [[Radio Station Belarus]] | accessdate = 20 May 2012 | title = Belteleradiocompany continues preparations for the Eurovision-2012 | date = 13 April 2012}}</ref>
During an interview, Dmitriy Karyakin explained that the song "says that if we all believe in and go to our goal, then we will achieve it, despite all the difficulties. Only faith can help us. And if we are all together, it will also save us."<ref>{{Cite web| url = http://ann.az/en/?p=33726 | publisher = Ann.az | accessdate = 20 May 2012 | title = Belarus’s Eurovision-2012 entry: Why not Azerbaijan as favorite? | date = 7 April 2012}}</ref>
The song was performed in the second semi-final finishing 16th of 18 entrants and failed to reach the Eurovision grand final.
